{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c6c8390a-c7d0-4f72-8927-47a042453c67","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 / .NET 10 introduces **first-class span types**: `T[]` now implicitly converts to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` in more contexts, including extension-method overload resolution.\n\n**Before (.NET 9):** `array.Contains(num)` resolved to:\n`Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)`\n\n**After (.NET 10):** It now resolves to:\n`MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — expression trees cannot represent ref struct values or method calls involving them. So the expression tree either fails to compile or fails at interpretation time.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the `Enumerable` overload again. Two options:\n\n**Option A — cast to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — static call syntax:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains`, which uses `IEnumerable<T>` (not a ref struct) and is representable in expression trees.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4bde2887-94ea-4020-ba3e-7946d1fd0697","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays. Let me think about what changed.\n\nIn .NET 10 / C# 14, there's a significant change related to how extension methods work. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's a change related to how `Enumerable.Contains()` vs the new extension member resolution works.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is likely related to the fact that in C# 14 / .NET 10, the `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<T>()` method resolution changed. \n\n\nIn .NET 9, calling `Contains` on an `int[]` resolves to the LINQ extension method `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>()`. But in .NET 10, there's likely a new overload in `System.MemoryExtensions` that works with `Span<T>` or `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and since arrays implicitly convert to spans, the method resolution priority might have shifted, causing a breaking change in how the method gets selected.\n\nThe real issue is that expression trees can't represent calls to methods involving `Span<T>` or `ReadOnlySpan<T>` because spans are ref structs and can't be used in that context. cause the expression tree is built successfully at compile time, but then fails at runtime when the interpreter tries to execute it because it encounters the `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameter that can't be handled. Or maybe the resolution to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` happens differently than I'm thinking.\n\nLet me focus on what actually changed in .NET 10 — likely the new span-related features and implicit conversions are affecting how method overload resolution works with expression trees. a different way. Let me think about whether the error could actually be a runtime error instead of compile-time.\n\nIf the expression tree is being constructed dynamically at runtime—maybe through reflection or a library like EF Core—then the error would only surface when the tree is compiled or executed. Or perhaps there's a .NET 10 change in how `Enumerable.Contains` is handled in expression trees, or the interpreter has a bug when processing certain method calls. I should consider what specific breaking changes came with .NET 10 that might affect expression tree compilation or interpretation.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is an overload resolution change in C# 14 and .NET 10. When you call `Contains` on an array, it now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains` which takes a `ReadOnlySpan<T>` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct, it can't be used in expression trees, which causes the runtime failure. The fix would be to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` to force the correct overload resolution. might not be the preferred overload. In C# 13+, the compiler prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains` for arrays, but that method takes a `ReadOnlySpan<T>` which is a ref struct and can't be used in expression trees. So the real issue is that the overload resolution has shifted to something incompatible with expression tree compilation. which makes `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` first-class citizens with broader implicit conversion support. In .NET 10 / C# 14, the `MemoryExtensions.Contains` overload for `ReadOnlySpan<T>` now wins overload resolution over `Enumerable.Contains` when called on an array, since the conversion from `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is considered better than converting to `IEnumerable<T>`. The problem is that when this call appears inside an expression tree lambda, the compiler can't represent it because `ReadOnlySpan<T>` isn't supported in expression trees.\n\nThe runtime error could occur if the expression tree was constructed manually via the Expression API or if pre-compiled code is running on the new runtime. I should explain the overload resolution change as the root cause, while noting it could manifest as either a compile-time or runtime error depending on how the expression tree is built. The most likely explanation is that C# 14's first-class span support and implicit `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions cause `MemoryExtensions.Contains` to win over `Enumerable.Contains` during overload resolution, but expression trees can't handle ref structs, creating a compilation or runtime failure depending on the context. emit a compile-time error about ref struct types not being allowed in expression trees. But the user mentioned a runtime error, which suggests either they're being imprecise about when the failure occurs, or the expression tree was built differently—maybe through the Expression API directly rather than a lambda, which could cause different behavior at runtime depending on how it's compiled or interpreted.\n\nI think the most likely explanation is that .NET 10 with C# 14 introduced changes to how overload resolution works with Span types, making implicit conversions from arrays to `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` participate in extension method resolution. This means `array.Contains(x)` now resolves differently than before, which could break existing code that relied on the old behavior.","outputTokens":4459,"requestId":"6845:210779:12F0ED:18DDA2:69FFD7D2"},"id":"01d18217-1fb9-44ca-8750-bc6fb0f00b9b","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:58:16.977Z","parentId":"77bd1425-e84a-4daa-a35a-de558e25becb"}
